- - - ( Arrays ) - - -



** ( Example (1) All Valid Array Values ):

• str: ["hello"]
• num: [123]
• bool: [true]
• nul: [null]
• undef: [undefined]
• obj: [{ key: "value" }]
• arr: [[1, 2, 3]]
• func: [function() { return "hi"; }]
• sym: [Symbol("id")]
• big: [123n]

- Arrays can store mixed types  
  e.g. [1, "two", true, null]



** ( Example (2) Create Empty Array ):

// Both syntax create an empty array
• const arr = [];
• const arr = new Array();

- You can start empty and add values later.



** ( Example (3) Create & Initialize Array ):

• const fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Mango"];

- Arrays are zero-indexed: fruits[0] is "Apple"



** ( Example (4) Access & Modify Array Values ):

// Accessing
• fruits[1]; // Outputs: "Banana"

// Modifying
• fruits[1] = "Peach"; //  Outputs: ["Apple", "Peach", "Mango"]

// Adding New Values
• fruits.push("Grapes");    // Add to end
• fruits.unshift("Orange"); // Add to start

// Removing Values
• fruits.pop();     // Removes last
• fruits.shift();   // Removes first

// Output Array length
• fruits.length; // e.g. 3



** ( Example (5) Spread Operator with Arrays ):

- "..." spreads array items into another array or function

const nums = [1, 2, 3]; // Array

• const copy = [...nums]; // [1, 2, 3]

• const merged = [...nums, 4, 5]; // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]